                What Is Trading?
        </div>

        <section class="text-box">
            
            <p1>
                Trading is buying and selling assets with the objective of making a profit. In a financial market, trading refers to shares, goods and currencies.
                You can complete a trade through an exchange or over the counter (OTC). An exchange is a platform where brokers trade different financial instruments in the market on behalf of their clients. 
                Large organisations usually use the stock exchange method. An OTC trade happens directly between two parties. OTC trading is a more informal process that allows both parties to complete the trade by email or phone.
            </p1>
            <p1>
                You can get exposure to markets as diverse as the S&P 500, the FTSE 100, global currencies like the US dollar or Japanese yen, or even commodities like lean hog or cattle.
                Trading can be done for various purposes, from investing and hedging risk to speculating on market movements.
            </p1>
        </section>

        <section class="mt-4">
            <table class="trading-terms-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Types Of Trading </th>
                    <th>What each type of Trading means</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Swing Trading</td>
                    <td>Strategy focusing on taking advantage of short to medium-term price patterns in the market.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Position Trading</td>
                    <td>A long-term strategy where traders hold positions for longer periods, often weeks or months.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Scalping</td>
                    <td>A strategy that involves making numerous trades to profit from small market movements.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Day Trading</td>
                    <td>Buying and selling securities within the same trading day, closing positions by the end of the day.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Fundamental Trading</td>
                    <td>Trading strategy based on fundamental analysis, which involves evaluating a security's intrinsic value.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Technical Trading</td>
                    <td>Using technical analysis and chart patterns to predict future price movements based on past trends.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Shares</td>
                    <td>Units of ownership in a company, representing a portion of the corporation's assets and earnings.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Commodities</td>
                    <td>Basic goods used in commerce that are interchangeable with other goods of the same type.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Delivery Trading</td>
                    <td>Buying stocks and holding them for more than a day, with the intention of delivery to the investor.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
            </table>
